Statistical Audit of the Global Index on Responsible AI (GIRAI)

Luciano Borgoglio

2024-06-07

Executive summary and conclusions

  • The Global Index on Responsible AI is found to be statistically very sound in terms of the correlation structure and in terms of the presence of a very significant latent variable underlying the data found via Principal Component Analysis.

  • The framework is very consistent: the pillars measure a latent variable that accounts for a large amount (83.5%) of the variability of the data (well above the threshold of 70% usually considered good practice for composite indexes).

  • Many indicators present salient quality attributes: specially too many zeroes and/or too few unique values, but the aggregation is successful in getting pillars and index scores with much better statistical qualities. This trait, of abundance of zeroes, is unsuprising to the extent that we are assessing very emergent phenomena.

  • The correlation structure of the indicators belonging to each pillar is very good, with a vast majority of correlations in desired ranges: the Index is statistically very sound also at the level of the indicators that compose each pillar.

  • The correlation structure is also very good between the indicators and the pillar to which they belong, between the indicators and the index and between the pillars themselves.

  • Consistency of the framework in terms of (very high) Cronbach’s Alpha confirms the soundness of the index assessed via the structure of correlations and Principal Components Analysis.

  • The framework was found very sound the way it already is, but some simulations were run just for illustration purposes in the appendix.

  • Equal weighting of the pillars was experimented with, suggested by PCA weights and optimization procedures, and also in relation to the conceptual equal essentiality or complementarity of them.

  • Some other aggregation formulas for the pillars, like a geometric weighted mean, was also explored in order to allow for less than perfect compensation between them (i.e.: considering them “essentials”). Exclusion of some indicators were also experimented with.

  • The quality attributes of the indicators might be improved and costs might be reduced if eventually the data collection were to be semi-automated. Developing automated agents to perform this task with the researchers’ supervision might yield more granular, well-behaved and nuanced data with more distinct values, making more of a continuum and less of a set of categories. This would also save time, unify methods for all regions/hubs and assess a bigger set of dimensions more accurately. The fact that the data is the outcome of primarily an online research, makes the task, at least in principle, quite prone to semi-automation. This would, of course, entail extensive experimentation, but looks like a promising path to explore.

  • In conclusion, the Global Index on Responsible AI is very statistically sound as it is. There is very little room (or need) to simplify and/or improve the index.

Introduction

This notebook presents a full statistical audit of the Global Index on Responsible AI (GIRAI). The main objectives are to assess the statistical soundness of the index and (if necessary) to suggest changes in the direction of improving it.

We will be leveraging the R package COINr (CRAN, 2023) whenever possible, which embeds current best practices for building and analyzing composite indexes, in a user-friendly framework that the GIRAI team will be able to use, with minimal adaptation, for other indexes or future versions of this one. The package was developed by European Commission’s Joint Research Centre, a renowned authority in statistical audits.

We will go through the full data cycle in this document: download the data, perform the analysis, present the results and provide the recommendations. This allows for a consistent and straightforward procedure that also opens the door for a full automation of the whole process.

This document can be read in a browser, where you will be able to interact with tables and graphs. The outputs of the chunks of code can be quite verbose but a choice has been made of keeping them, in order to show fully the inner workings of the processes and for GIRAI team to adapt it more easily for other uses.

We have a dataset of 4031 lines and 112 columns. The dataset is machine readable, the naming of variables are intuitive and the documentation is clear. All numeric and character fields are correctly formatted and the names of the variables are intuitive.

We will remove Bosnia and Herzegovina since doesn’t enter the ranking. We will also be working with scoring thematic areas only, since they are the only ones that get into the index calculation. We can therefore also delete all non-scoring thematic areas data from our database:

# Filter rows where "scoring" is not equal to "non-scoring" and let go BIH
GIRAI_dataset <- GIRAI_dataset %>%
  filter(scoring != "non-scoring", ISO_alpha3_code != "BIH")

Next, we will transform the dataframe in order to fit it into a COIN, the R object that will be manipulated by COINr package.

COINr data preprocessing

As mentioned, throughout this audit we will make extensive use of COINr. This R package provides a harmonised development environment for composite indicators that includes all common operations from indicator selection, data treatment and imputation up to aggregation, presentation of results and uncertainty analysis. COINr enables development, visualisation and exploration of methodological variations, and encourages transparency and reproducibility. This enables a neat and structured environment, simplifies the syntax of functions, and also allows comparisons between different versions of the same index, as well as global sensitivity analysis (Becker et al, 2022).

We will preprocess the data in order to be suitable for the COINr workflow. From the database downloaded, we now need to build two dataframes with the following schema:

  1. iData: A dataframe that has the countries in rows and indicators in columns.

The first columns should be uName and uCode; then all indicators.

  1. iMeta: A dataframe that has the indicators in rows and the following columns:

         * Level
     * iCode
     * iName
     * Direction
     * Weight 
     * Unit
     * Parent
     * Type

iData dataframe

The iData dataframe is where the bulk of the data from the downloaded database will be located. We will be extracting the indicators, which is the adequate level of analysis for a statistical audit of the index.

We will transform the downloaded dataframe into the desired format where the rows represent countries and the columns represent indicators (with cell values from the score column) and we will rename the columns suitably for the processing that COINr will do later.

In this process, we will create columns for all 57 indicators (3 pillars x 19 thematic areas). Since each indicator can be considered the intersection between a pillar and a thematic area, the naming we will use will follow that closely: for the indicator of pillar Frameworks and thematic area Bias and Unfair Discrimination (thematic area number 1), the indicator will be coded as fr_ta1 and named Frameworks - Bias and Unfair Discrimination.

We will take the normalised values from the details database, since the type of normalisation is not a major concern for their different options to be simulated here (as opposed to aggregation by geometric or arithmetic mean, weighting of pillars, inclusion/exclusion of indicators, etc., which might more relevant topics for the stakeholders). The values for the indicators that we will take for this audit are not only normalised but also adjusted for effectiveness via secondary sources (see Methodology).

Thematic areas are indexed by arranging the dimensions alphabetically and then arranging alphabetically the thematic areas belonging to each (as is the common usage so far), information that we will locate in thematic_areas dataframe along with the whole hierarchical structure that includes the aggregation of thematic areas into sub dimensions and dimensions:

# Get a list of thematic areas ordered within dimensions which are also ordered alphabetically 
thematic_areas <- GIRAI_dataset %>%
  select(dimension, sub_dimension, thematic_area) %>%  # Include sub_dimension
  distinct() %>%
  arrange(dimension, sub_dimension, thematic_area) %>%
  mutate(
    ta_index = sprintf("%02d", row_number()),  # Creates a number for each thematic area with two digits
    ta_code = paste0("ta", ta_index)  # Generate ta_code from ta_index
  )

thematic_areas %>%
  reactable()

We have now 19 (scoring) thematic areas.

Indicators and country codes and names

# Create a distinct dataset of ISO_alpha3_code and country
iData <- GIRAI_dataset %>%
  distinct(ISO_alpha3_code, country) %>%
  rename(uCode = ISO_alpha3_code, uName = country)

# Function to merge thematic scores with base data
merge_thematic_scores <- function(base_data, score_data, thematic_area_index, prefix, score_col) {
  # Retrieve the name of the thematic area using the index
  thematic_area_name <- thematic_areas$thematic_area[thematic_area_index]
  
  # Filter data for the current thematic area
  score_df <- score_data %>%
    filter(thematic_area == thematic_area_name) %>%
    select(uCode = ISO_alpha3_code, score = {{ score_col }}) 

  # Format the thematic_area_index as two digits and rename the 'score' column
  colnames(score_df)[which(colnames(score_df) == "score")] <- paste0(prefix, "_ta", sprintf("%02d", thematic_area_index))

  # Join scores back to the main dataframe
  base_data <- left_join(base_data, score_df, by = "uCode")
  
  return(base_data)
}

# Loop through each index of thematic areas using adjusted (and normalised) values
for (index in seq_along(thematic_areas$thematic_area)) {
  iData <- merge_thematic_scores(iData, GIRAI_dataset, index, "fr", "fr_adjust_score")
  iData <- merge_thematic_scores(iData, GIRAI_dataset, index, "ga", "ga_adjust_score")
  iData <- merge_thematic_scores(iData, GIRAI_dataset, index, "nsa", "nsa_adjust_score")
}

We have now a dataframe of 138 rows (countries) * 59 columns (3 pillars x 19 thematic areas = 57 -normalised and adjusted- primary indicators and 2 other columns -located at the beggining- with countries’ -ISO3- codes and names).

Even if dimensions and sub dimensions don’t enter the actual scoring, it will be useful to have them in the COIN object in order to exploit, for instance, the package’s visualization capabilities. Crossings

We will build other auxiliary (also non-scoring) indicators that will exploit the double-sided design of the index. These indicators are dimensions in pillar. The other way around, pillars in dimension, yields the same results as will be shown later, which is why they will be omitted.

Dimensions in pillar

The total score for the pillar for a unit is the mean of all indicators corresponding to that pillar. The naming convention will put first the code of the dimension, then a slash, then the pillar.

For instance, for the case of Frameworks, the total score for Canada (CAN) would be:

\[\text{fr}_{\text{CAN}} = \frac{\text{fr_ta1}_{\text{CAN}} + \text{fr_ta2}_{\text{CAN}} + \ldots + \text{fr_ta19}_{\text{CAN}}}{19}\]

We can compute partial means/scores from this, corresponding to each dimension (within the pillar). For instance, for the case of Human Rights and AI in Frameworks pillar:

\[\text{hr_fr}_{\text{CAN}} = \frac{\text{fr_ta1}_{\text{CAN}} + \text{fr_ta2}_{\text{CAN}} + \cdots + \text{fr_ta7}_{\text{CAN}}}{7}\]

For National Responsible AI Capacities dimension in Government actions pillar:

\[\text{cap_ga}_{\text{CAN}} = \frac{\text{ga_ta8}_{\text{CAN}} + \ldots + \text{ga_ta10}_{\text{CAN}}}{3}\]

For Non-state Actors dimension in Responsible AI Governance pillar:

\[\text{gov_nsa}_{\text{CAN}} = \frac{\text{nsa_ta11}_{\text{CAN}} + \text{nsa_ta12}_{\text{CAN}} + \ldots + \text{nsa_ta19}_{\text{CAN}}}{9}\]

The same logic applies for the other six crossings. Now, let us create these new nine variables in iData dataframe:

# Calculation of dimensions in pillars
iData <- iData %>%
  mutate(
    hr_fr = rowMeans(select(., starts_with("fr_ta"))[, 1:7]),
    hr_ga = rowMeans(select(., starts_with("ga_ta"))[, 1:7]),
    hr_nsa = rowMeans(select(., starts_with("nsa_ta"))[, 1:7]),
    cap_fr = rowMeans(select(., starts_with("fr_ta"))[, 8:10]),
    cap_ga = rowMeans(select(., starts_with("ga_ta"))[, 8:10]),
    cap_nsa = rowMeans(select(., starts_with("nsa_ta"))[, 8:10]),
    gov_fr = rowMeans(select(., starts_with("fr_ta"))[, 11:19]),
    gov_ga = rowMeans(select(., starts_with("ga_ta"))[, 11:19]),
    gov_nsa = rowMeans(select(., starts_with("nsa_ta"))[, 11:19])
  )

So far, we have iData dataframe with 97 variables (from details plus some aggregations from it) for our 138 countries.

Pillars in dimension

For the sake of completeness, we will confirm the commutative property of the crossings, that is, that the order doesn’t alter the product, which means that the pillars in dimensions calculation would yield the same results as the dimensions in pillar calculation.

The total score for the dimension for a unit (country or groups of them) is the sum of all indicators corresponding to that dimension (from pillars fr, ga and nsa). The naming convention will put first the code of the pillar, then a slash, then the dimension.

For instance, for the case of Human Rights and AI, the total score for Canada (CAN) would be the mean of all indicators belonging to that dimension, from any pillar:

\[\text{hr}_{\text{CAN}} = \frac{{\text{fr_ta1}_{\text{CAN}} + \text{ga_ta1}_{\text{CAN}} + \text{nsa_ta1}_{\text{CAN}} + \ldots + \text{fr_ta7}_{\text{CAN}} + \text{ga_ta7}_{\text{CAN}} + \text{nsa_ta7}_{\text{CAN}}}}{21}\]

We can compute partial means from this, corresponding to each pillar. For instance, for the case of Frameworks:

\[\text{fr_hr} = \frac{{\text{fr_ta1}_{\text{CAN}} + \text{fr_ta2}_{\text{CAN}} + \ldots + \text{fr_ta7}_{\text{CAN}}}}{7}\]

Which is exactly the same expression we found for the Human Rights and AI dimension in Frameworks pillar before:

\[\text{fr_hr} = \text{hr_fr} = \frac{{\text{fr_ta1}_{\text{CAN}} + \text{fr_ta2}_{\text{CAN}} + \ldots + \text{fr_ta7}_{\text{CAN}}}}{7}\]

Hence, we will not calculate the pillars in dimension crossings since they yield the same results as the dimensions in pillar already calculated.

# Function to fill in the indicator names
fill_indicator_names <- function(code) {
  if (grepl("^fr", code)) {
    # Extract the number from the column name
    number <- as.numeric(gsub("fr_ta", "", code))
    # Look up the thematic area name using the number
    thematic_area <- thematic_areas$thematic_area[thematic_areas$ta_index == number]
    return(paste("Frameworks -", thematic_area))
  } else if (grepl("^ga", code)) {
    number <- as.numeric(gsub("ga_ta", "", code))
    thematic_area <- thematic_areas$thematic_area[thematic_areas$ta_index == number]
    return(paste("Government Actions -", thematic_area))
  } else if (grepl("^nsa", code)) {
    number <- as.numeric(gsub("nsa_ta", "", code))
    thematic_area <- thematic_areas$thematic_area[thematic_areas$ta_index == number]
    return(paste("Non-State Actors -", thematic_area))
  } else if (grepl("^sec", code)) {
    # Match the code to the 'code' in the secondary_indicators and fetch the corresponding 'name'
    indicator_name <- secondary_indicators$name[secondary_indicators$code == code]
    return(indicator_name)
  } else {
    return(NA) # Return NA for codes not matching any pattern
  }
}

map_combinations_to_names <- function(code) {
  if (startsWith(code, "hr")) {
    pillar_name <- "Human Rights and AI"
  } else if (startsWith(code, "cap")) {
    pillar_name <- "National Responsible AI Capacities"
  } else if (startsWith(code, "gov")) {
    pillar_name <- "Responsible AI Governance"
  } else {
    return(NA)
  }
  
  if (endsWith(code, "fr")) {
    thematic_area <- "Frameworks"
  } else if (endsWith(code, "ga")) {
    thematic_area <- "Government Actions"
  } else if (endsWith(code, "nsa")) {
    thematic_area <- "Non-State Actors"
  } else {
    return(NA)
  }
  
  return(paste(pillar_name, thematic_area, sep = " - "))
}

Correlation analysis and statistical coherence

The assessment of statistical coherence involves a comprehensive analysis of indicator correlations across multiple levels. Correlation analysis serves as a vital tool for evaluating the degree to which observed data aligns with the underlying conceptual framework.

Within each level of the composite index, it is desirable to observe positive and statistically significant correlations among the constituent indicators. To gauge the strength of these correlations, the Joint Research Centre-COIN recommends the use of a correlation threshold of 0.3. When the correlation coefficient exceeds this threshold, it signifies a substantial shared variability between two elements, providing evidence of a significant relationship.

Furthermore, it is crucial to ensure that the framework avoids redundancy, which can manifest as excessively high correlations, typically at or above 0.9. Such high correlations indicate collinearity between two indicators, which could lead to issues like double counting and, consequently, an undue weighting of the same underlying phenomenon in the index. Fortunately, these correlation thresholds are seamlessly integrated into the COIN framework, facilitating a very systematic evaluation (and eventually automatable) of statistical coherence.

In the ensuing sections, we will present correlation analyses across various dimensions. This will encompass correlations among indicators within the same pillar, correlations between indicators and their aggregate levels (pillars and the overall index), correlations between individual pillars and the composite index and between the pillars themselves.

Frameworks

Let us check the correlation structure of indicators within Frameworks pillar:

plot_corr(GIRAI, dset = "Aggregated", iCodes = list("fr"), Levels = 1, flagcolours = TRUE)

Correlations in green are good enough, between 0.3 and 0.9, as mentioned before. When not shown, they are statistically insignificant and when shown but in gray, they are significant but lower than the threshold (0.3).

The general structure of correlations of this pillar is very good. fr_ta_10 has 16 problematic (weak) correlations out of 18, which sets it quite apart from this pillar. fr_ta_16 follows with 9. All the rest have 2 or less, which makes this pillar very sound anyway. Both indicators were flagged before, as possibly having outliers but having mostly a lot of zeroes.

All the correlations of the indicators of Frameworks to the actual pillar and also to the Index are good, the lowest and closest to the lower threshold of correlation to its pillar being fr_ta10 and fr_ta16, already flagged above.

All in all, the correlation structure of indicators within pillars, as proof of the statistical coherence of the framework, is very good.

Pillars among themselves

Let us check the correlation structure of the pillars. This level of aggregation holds utmost significance as it serves as a crucial test for the coherence and integrity of the overarching concept of the index:

plot_corr(GIRAI, dset = "Aggregated", Levels = 2, flagcolours = TRUE)

All correlations are in the desired ranges for the pillars, which shows strong support for the framework of the index.

Pillars to index

Let us check the correlation between the pillars and the index:

plot_corr(GIRAI, dset = "Aggregated", Levels = c(2,3), flagcolours = TRUE)

ga and fr pillars have correlations to the index above the threshold of 0.9, signalling in principle some redundancy in the concept they measure in relation to the information brought by the index. The effectiveness correction seems to have worsened a little this particular structure of correlations (quite naturally. the separate pillar of secondary sources had the lowest correlation to the index before).

This might be difficult to overcome because in fact all the three correlations are quite high now. If we were to optimise weights (as will be done later) in order to have equal correlations to the index, this equal correlation will be also higher than 0.9, turning all three correlations outside the proper range. This result can be seen in other statistical audits without considering it a problem per se.

As a matter of fact, we can consider that in the index the State ultimately weights two thirds (fr and ga), so it is natural that any of fr or ga can “anticipate” the index since they measure different aspects of the same agent and also the correlation they have is the highest in the (correlations) matrix of pillars, making them different conceptually but in practice very statistically related aspects of the same agent. Finally, and conversely, the lowest correlation of nsa to the (two-thirds State) index is only natural since is the only non-state pillar of the three.

All in all, the structure of correlations seems justifiable as it is and the trait of the high correlation between fr and ga can be considered more a (somewhat expected) empirical finding and less of an actual problem.

Conclusions

The correlation structure within the indicators of each pillar, between the indicators and their respective pillars and index, within pillars, and between pillars and index is very good, adding substantial evidence to the soundness of the framework.

Cronbach’s Alpha

Another alternative way to check the internal consistency of the indicators within each pillar and for the overall index is Cronbach’s Alpha. The coefficient ranges from 0 to 1, with higher values indicating greater internal consistency. A low Alpha (close to 0) suggests that the items in the scale do not consistently measure the same construct. This could be due to the inclusion of unrelated or contradictory items. A moderate Alpha (generally between 0.7 and 0.9, depending on the field) indicates some degree of internal consistency but leaves room for improvement. A high Alpha (close to 1) indicates strong internal consistency, implying that the items in the scale are highly correlated with each other and effectively measure the underlying construct. This is desirable when developing a reliable index.

For Frameworks:

get_cronbach(GIRAI, dset = "Aggregated", iCodes = "fr", Level = 1) # Indicator level
## [1] 0.9497216

For Government Actions:

get_cronbach(GIRAI, dset = "Aggregated", iCodes = "ga", Level = 1) # Indicator level
## [1] 0.9478158

For Non-State Actors:

get_cronbach(GIRAI, dset = "Aggregated", iCodes = "nsa", Level = 1) # Indicator level
## [1] 0.9609769

For the overall index:

get_cronbach(GIRAI, dset = "Aggregated", iCodes = "index", Level = 1) # Indicator level
## [1] 0.9781373

Cronbach’s Alpha is very high (close to 1) and similar for all pillars, adding evidence to the statistical soundness of each. The value at the level of the index, for all indicators, is even higher: the index effectively combining indicators from different pillars and measuring a broader, more nuanced concept. The individual pillars captures specific aspects, while the index assesses the overarching construct. This results, complementary to the correlation before and PCA analyses next, adds to the soundness of the framework.

Principal Component Analysis

Continuing our exploration of statistical coherence, we delve into a principal component analysis (PCA). This analytical step serves to gauge the alignment between our conceptual framework and the empirical data. The overarching goal is to identify a single principal component capable of elucidating over 70% of the total variance (European Comission, 2022). Meeting these criteria signifies the existence of a unifying, one-dimensional phenomenon that underpins the various pillars. The same analysis will be performed at the level of indicators composing each of the pillars. In each of these levels, the objective is to assess the presence of a latent variable that the pillars of the index or the indicators of each pillar are supposed to be measuring.

By conducting PCA, we aim to distill the complex interplay of indicators into a more parsimonious representation, shedding light on the fundamental structure of our composite index. This not only enhances our understanding of the data but also bolsters the index’s credibility by corroborating its conceptual underpinnings through rigorous statistical analysis.

Pillar level

Here we take the database formed by the pillars to check if there is a strong latent variable “behind” them.

# PCA 
pillar_pca <- get_PCA(GIRAI, dset = "Aggregated", Level = 2, by_groups = FALSE, out2 = "list", nowarnings = FALSE)

fviz_eig(pillar_pca$PCAresults$All$PCAres, addlabels = TRUE)

The first dimension accounts for 83.5% of variance and the second follows very far with just 10.4%. This means that the PCA analysis yields evidence of a very strong latent variable underlying the pillars, which gives support to the framework, quite in excess of the mentioned 70% threshold considered best practice. Dimensions 3 and 4 are less important, with 8.2% and 5% of explained variance. This allows a two-dimensional representation to be sufficient, accounting for 93.8% of the variance of the dataset of the pillars. In other words, only 6.1% of information is lost by compressing the dataset of the pillars into these two artificial variables that combines the pillars linearly.

Now, let us project the pillars in the space of the first 2 principal components (which, as we said, allows for a sufficient representation):

fviz_pca_var(pillar_pca$PCAresults$All$PCAres, repel = TRUE)

Pillars ga and nsa are quite closely aligned, meaning they measure quite related aspects. fr is quite orthogonal to them both, seemingly measuring a quite different concept in relation to ga and nsa.

Now let us explore the contributions of the pillars to each dimension:

fviz_contrib(pillar_pca$PCAresults$All$PCAres, choice = "var")

The red dashed line on the graph below indicates the expected average contribution of each pillar to the first dimension. If the contribution of the variables were uniform, the expected value would be 1/length(variables) = 1/3. For a given component, a variable with a contribution larger than this cutoff point could be considered as important in contributing to the component. Frameworks lies just a little below such threshold. The normalised version (constrained to sum to 1) of these contributions are called PCA weights and will be explored later to inform experimenting with a different set of weights.

Let us do the same with the second component:

fviz_contrib(pillar_pca$PCAresults$All$PCAres, choice = "var", axes = 2)

Turning to the factor loadings of the second component, which is less important than the first (by definition), the pattern indicates the presence of a second latent dimension in the data, one that is orthogonal or unrelated to the first; within this dimension, fr emerges as a particularly strong variable. Since the index is supposed to measure one latent variable related to Responsible AI, the pertinence of the second, less important and orthogonal dimension, should be put to the test. Nevertheless, fr has a significant loading to dimension 1 as well, which means that it also contributes significantly to the main latent dimension present in the data while also providing expression of some other aspects (presence in dimension 2). Also, the factor loading of nsa is quite significant to this second dimension too, and less so ga. Finally, this second dimensions accounts for a small proportion of the total variance of the dataset (10.4%).

Indicators within pillars

Let us now perform PCA again but with the indicators conforming each pillar, to see if each pillar has a distinct latent dimension, in order to justify the existence of each pillar (and the grouping of indicators they imply) in the first place. We found that the index indeed references a large latent variable, now we turn our attention to each pillar. There are no standards as to how much is enough for the pillars, as in the 70% percent mentioned before for the index.

We will run the analysis for all the pillars at once and then analyze each in turn.

ind_pillar_pca <- get_PCA(GIRAI, dset = "Aggregated", Level = 1, by_groups = TRUE, out2 = "list", nowarnings = FALSE)

Frameworks

Let us check the results of PCA on the indicators of Frameworks pillar:

fviz_eig(ind_pillar_pca$PCAresults$fr$PCAres, addlabels = TRUE)

The first component of the set of indicators in the Frameworks pillar accounts for 53.1% of the variance and the second for just 8.5%. Hence, there is a distinct latent variable behind the indicators of this pillar. The data doesn’t reject that there is one main dimension underlying the pillar, susceptible to be measured with this set of indicators.

A point of caution here: this doesn’t imply that this dimension is actually anything substantially enough like “Frameworks” to deserve that name, but it does say that the indicators of the pillars measure mainly (but certainly not exclusively) one dimension, which might or might not be anything like the concept “Frameworks” in the real world (which is something to be checked by other means). This, of course, applies to all our other findings of this kind.

Government actions

Let us check the results of PCA on the indicators of Government actions pillar:

fviz_eig(ind_pillar_pca$PCAresults$ga$PCAres, addlabels = TRUE)

52.4% for first component, distant second with 5.8%, making this pillar also quite sound in this respect.

Non-state actors

Let us check the results of PCA on the indicators of Non-state actors pillar:

fviz_eig(ind_pillar_pca$PCAresults$nsa$PCAres, addlabels = TRUE)

59.9% for first component, distant second with 4.6%, making this pillar sound as well.

Conclusions

The pillars show the presence of a strong latent variable that accounts for a percentage of variance (83.5%) beyond the minimum threshold considered good practice (70%; European Comission, 2022), making the index very sound in this respect.

Non-state actors is the most sound pillar in these terms, followed by Frameworks and Government Actions. All pillars seem to have significant latent variables behind the indicators that conform each with distant second, in importance, dimensions, thus providing strong support to the framework.

Leave-one-out analysis

How much are the ranking changed by removing individual indicators or pillars? One way of looking at indicator “importance” in a composite indicator is via correlations. A different way is to see what happens if we remove the indicator completely from the framework. If removing an indicator or a whole aggregation of indicators results in very little rank change, it is one indication that perhaps it is not necessary to include it.

Pillars on Index

pillar_loo <- remove_elements(GIRAI, Level = 2, dset = "Aggregated", iCode = "index", quietly = TRUE)

# Define a color palette with four distinct colors
colors <- c("#1f78b4", "#33a02c", "#e31a1c", "#ff7f00")

ggplot(data = data.frame(Pillar = names(pillar_loo$MeanAbsDiff[-1]),
                         Impact = pillar_loo$MeanAbsDiff[-1]),
       aes(x = Pillar, y = Impact, fill = Pillar)) + 
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  geom_text(aes(label = round(Impact, 1)), vjust = -0.5, color = "black", size = 3) +  
  scale_fill_manual(values = colors) +  # Assign colors to the bars
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1))

The impact of removing ga is the biggest (8) positions change in average), followed by fr with 7.2 and, last, nsa with 4.

Indicators on Index

Let’s do the same exercise with the whole set of indicators:

ind_loo <- remove_elements(GIRAI, Level = 1, dset = "Aggregated", iCode = "index", quietly = TRUE)

# Define the colors
colors <- c("#1f78b4", "#33a02c", "#e31a1c", "#ff7f00")

# Create a data frame with an additional column for the Pillar Type
data <- data.frame(
  Pillar = names(ind_loo$MeanAbsDiff[-1]),
  Impact = ind_loo$MeanAbsDiff[-1],
  PillarType = substr(names(ind_loo$MeanAbsDiff[-1]), 1, 3)  # Extract first 3 characters as Pillar Type
)

# Plot with colors based on pillar type and facet by pillar type
ggplot(data = data, aes(x = Pillar, y = Impact, fill = PillarType)) + 
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  scale_fill_manual(values = colors) +  # Use predefined colors

  facet_wrap(~ PillarType, scales = "free_x", ncol = 1)  # Create vertical facets

The impact of removing individual indicators ranges from a more than 1.5 positions change in average for ga_ta08 and a little more than 0.3 for nsa_ta16. The impact is not too variable and quite low in general; no individual indicators dominate the ranking and the average change in results is always much lower than those of the pillars found before, respecting in this manner the hierarchy of the framework and thus supporting it.

Uncertainty analysis

Statistical analysis of composite indicators often involves making assumptions that can influence how countries are ranked. Even with careful development, some level of uncertainty remains. To address this, we can compare results under different scenarios. Existing research suggests using Monte Carlo simulations and multiple modeling techniques to assess the robustness of an index (i.e., how sensitive it is to changes in assumptions).

The first step in this process is identifying which assumptions might have a significant impact on rankings. This involves considering the underlying data, indicator selection, and methodological choices (e.g., imputation methods, outlier treatment, normalization techniques, aggregation methods, weights). While we can’t test every assumption, focusing on some key area with plausible alternatives is a good starting point.

We will allow the weights to change 15% up or down in 1000 replications of the experiment, in order to see the intervals in which the scores and rankings move. These ranges for the weights include the PCA and optimised weights for each pillar, that calls for almost equal weighting of them all (1/3).

# get nominal weights
w_nom <- GIRAI$Meta$Weights$Original

# build data frame specifying the levels to apply the noise at
noise_specs = data.frame(Level = 2,
                         NoiseFactor = 0.15)

# get 100 replications
noisy_wts <- get_noisy_weights(w = w_nom, noise_specs = noise_specs, Nrep = 1000)

# component of SA_specs for weights
l_weights <- list(Address = "$Log$Aggregate$w",
                  Distribution = noisy_wts,
                  Type = "discrete")

# create overall specification list
SA_specs <- list(
  Weights = l_weights
)

GIRAI$Log$Aggregate$w <- noisy_wts

set.seed(1)

UA_res <- get_sensitivity(GIRAI, SA_specs = SA_specs, N = 1000, SA_type = "UA",
                          dset = "Aggregated", iCode = "index", quietly = TRUE)

Let us see the results, for all countries, for top 10 and bottom 10.

plot_uncertainty(UA_res)

plot_uncertainty(UA_res, plot_units = "top10")

plot_uncertainty(UA_res, plot_units = "bottom10")

This graph shows how countries are ranked based on their scores. It considers the median rank across multiple simulations where pillar weights were changed (representing uncertainty in the weighting scheme). The graph also highlights the spread of ranks by showing the 5th and 95th percentile values; we can see that these confidence intervals are not wide, showing that the big uncertainty about the appropriate weights that we introduced didn’t affect that confidence very much.

We focus on ranks in this uncertainty analysis because scores can vary significantly depending on the chosen methodology. Ranks provide a more consistent comparison across different ways of building a composite indicator. Even if scores differ, the relative order of units (their rank) might remain similar. Let us have one number to synthesize this argument:

# Calculate the differences between Q95 and Q5
differences <- UA_res$RankStats$Q95 - UA_res$RankStats$Q5

# Calculate the mean of the differences
mean_difference <- mean(differences)

# Print the mean difference
print(mean_difference)
## [1] 2.342029

Adding noise to the pillar weights (+/- 15%), reflecting methodological uncertainty about their proper values, makes the interval between 5 and 95 percentiles to have a mean of more than two positions for the whole set of countries. If we consider the top 10 these intervals are smaller and for the first 7 positions they collapse to points.

That entails that if we take into account the uncertainty in the proper weights in this fashion, then only differences in rankings of more than two positions should be considered definite enough to separate them considering the whole ranking, whereas even smaller differences can be pointed out in the top 10.

Appendixes

Adjustment and comparisons

Even if the framework is sound as it is, for future reference of GIRAI team we will consider how the rankings would change when changing some aspects of the GIRAI methodology. In particular, we will consider:

  1. Using a different set weights (equal weighting and a different set of unequal weights)

  2. Using a geometric weighted mean instead of an arithmetic weighted mean (to introduce incomplete substitutability between the pillars, that is, considering them essentials of some sort)

  3. Letting some indicators go

Weights

Weights are used by most aggregation methods to optionally alter the contribution of each indicator in an aggregation group, as well as by aggregates themselves if they are further aggregated. Are the weights for the pillars stated previously “good” in some statistical sense?

PCA

We will inspect PCA results at a pillar level that we conducted before, to see the weights suggested by that procedure, normalising them (to constrain them to sum to 1) first:

# Assuming pillar_pca$PCAresults$All$wts is your vector of weights
weights <- pillar_pca$PCAresults$All$wts

# Normalize the weights
normalized_weights <- weights / sum(weights)

# Now the normalized weights will sum to 1
normalized_weights
## [1] 0.3240030 0.3404447 0.3355522

Those are the normalised weights suggested by PCA for fr, ga and nsa respectively. They are almost equal.

Optimisation

Now we will perform another different procedure to get “good” weights. While PCA is based on linear algebra, another way to statistically weight indicators is via numerical optimisation. Optimisation is a numerical search method which finds a set of values which maximise or minimise some criterion, called the “objective function”.

Here, we will search for the set of weights that results in equal influence (correlation) of the pillars (level 3) on the index. That is, the set of weights that make the correlations between the pillars and the index equal.

l_opt <- get_opt_weights(GIRAI, itarg = "equal", dset = "Aggregated",
Level = 2, out2 = "list")
## iterating... objective function = -10.0776590674977
## iterating... objective function = -10.6331906161101
## iterating... objective function = -9.74027927970573
## iterating... objective function = -9.89972969319927
## Optimisation successful!
l_opt$WeightsOpt$Weight[58:60]
## [1] 0.3548387 0.3225806 0.3225806

Again, this procedure suggest almost equal weighting for fr, ga and nsa.

Aggregation formula

We will explore the impact of using a geometric weighted mean to aggregate the pillars instead of the arithmetic weighted mean employed so far (indicators are aggregated, as before, with an arithmetic weighted mean). Geometric means don’t accept zeroes, so we will add the smallest quantity possible to all zero values in our modified custom function.

# Make a copy
GIRAI_geom <- GIRAI

# Custom weighted geometric mean
weighted_geo_mean_modified <- function(x, w, small_value = 0.000001) {
  # Add a small value to zero elements
  x[x == 0] <- small_value
  
  # Calculate the weighted geometric mean using a_gmean from coinr
  result <- a_gmean(x, w)
  
  return(result)
}

GIRAI_geom <- Aggregate(GIRAI_geom, dset = "Raw", f_ag = c("a_amean", "weighted_geo_mean_modified"))
## Written data set to .$Data$Aggregated
## (overwritten existing data set)
# Get results table
GIRAI_geom_results <- get_results(GIRAI_geom, dset = "Aggregated", tab_type = "Full") 

get_results(GIRAI_geom, dset = "Aggregated", tab_type = "Full") |>
  reactable()

Let us compare the rankings:

# compare index, sort by absolute rank difference
compare_coins(GIRAI, GIRAI_geom, dset = "Aggregated", iCode = "index",
              sort_by = "Abs.diff", decreasing = TRUE) |>
  reactable::reactable()

Costa Rica goes down 42 positions, Canada and China stay the same.

compare_coins(GIRAI, GIRAI_geom, dset = "Aggregated", iCode = "index",
              sort_by = "Abs.diff", decreasing = TRUE) |>
    summarise(mean_abs_diff = mean(Abs.diff))
##   mean_abs_diff
## 1      5.144928

The mean absolute difference is 5.14 positions in the ranking when choosing geometric mean as the aggregation formula for pillars.

Data imputation

Since there are no missing values, there is no need for imputation, but here we will develop the imputation part of the pipeline for completeness. The current methodology of the index uses GIRAI regions’ mean to impute missing values but here we will propose another technique to exploit the whole dataframe for the imputation of each value, Expected Maximization algorithm, from Amelia package:

i_EM <- function(x){
  # impute
  amOut <- Amelia::amelia(x, m = 1, p2s = 0, boot.type = "none")
  # return imputed data
  amOut$imputations[[1]]
}

# impute raw data set
GIRAI <- Impute(GIRAI, dset = "Raw", f_i = i_EM, impute_by = "df", group_level = 2)
## Written data set to .$Data$Imputed
GIRAI
## --------------
## A coin with...
## --------------
## Input:
##   Units: 138 (AFG, ALB, ARE, ...)
##   Indicators: 57 (fr_ta01, fr_ta02, fr_ta03, ...)
##   Denominators: 0 ()
##   Groups: 0 (none)
## 
## Structure:
##   Level 1 Indicator: 57 indicators (fr_ta01, fr_ta02, fr_ta03, ...) 
##   Level 2 Pillar: 3 groups (fr, ga, nsa) 
##   Level 3 Index: 1 groups (index) 
## 
## Data sets:
##   Raw (138 units)
##   Aggregated (138 units)
##   Screened (138 units)

No data is imputed, so Imputed dataframe is exactly like Raw.

Data treatment

From the previous analysis, it appears that there are 8 variables that have skewness and kurtosis exceeding appropriate thresholds and, hence, some treatment to become statistically acceptable might eventually be considered, if it weren’t for the fact that we established already that the reason behind the outliers is the abundance of zeroes (because of the very emergent quality of the phenomena assessed) and, hence, no treatment is deemed necessary. For completeness, we will go through the process to treat data in case of need of GIRAI team later on for other cases.

Skewness is a measure of the asymmetry of a distribution. A distribution is skewed to the right if it has a long tail on the right side and skewed to the left if it has a long tail on the left side. A distribution with a skewness of zero is perfectly symmetrical. Kurtosis, on the other hand, is a measure of the peakedness of a distribution. A distribution is said to be kurtotic if it has a higher peak and fatter tails than a normal distribution. A distribution with a kurtosis of 3 is considered to be normal.

Indicators with high skewness and kurtosis can be difficult to interpret and can lead to inaccurate results when used in composite indicators:

  • Skewness and kurtosis can affect the calculation of the mean and median. If an indicator is highly skewed or kurtotic, the mean and median may not be representative of the distribution. This can lead to inaccurate results when using the mean and median to calculate composite indicators. It is usually forgotten that the mean as a measure of central tendency is not applicable to any distribution, and these thresholds are informative of the cases in which it is actually not.

  • Skewness and kurtosis can affect the results of statistical tests. Many statistical tests assume that the data is normally distributed. If an indicator is highly skewed or kurtotic, the results of statistical tests may not be reliable. Even if the normality assumption is usually strictly not met in practice, surpassing the above mentioned thresholds means an actual rejection of such normality and casts doubt on the tests using the data.

  • Skewness and kurtosis can make it difficult to compare indicators. If indicators have different levels of skewness and kurtosis, it can be difficult to compare them directly. This can lead to inaccurate results when using composite indicators to rank countries or regions.

Overall, it is important to have indicators with low skewness and kurtosis to ensure that composite indicators are accurate and reliable, because it affects the summarizing measures of the distribution and also any statistical tests applied to them. Even being careful in the way the data is aggregated within the index, having good statistical properties in the data for other possible uses of the users might be conceivable.

We spotted eight indicators exceeding thresholds and, hence, would need further treatment to become acceptable. Acceptable in this context means having skewness lower (in absolute value) than 2 and kurtosis lower than 3.5 (also in absolute value), which is the usual standard in the development and analysis of composite indicators (Joint Research Centre, 2019).

As mentioned considering the emergent quality of the phenomena observed, it is precisely the abundance of zeroes what makes the distributions asymmetric (many points at the left, especially zeroes) and leptokurtotic (fatter tails, respect to a normal distribution, towards the right).

We will perform the treatment for the sole purpose of illustration and completeness of the infrastructure. Let us list the indicators with skewness and kurtosis outside proper thresholds:

get_stats(GIRAI, dset = "Raw", out2 = "df") %>%
  # Filter rows where Flag.SkewKurt is "OUT"
  filter(Flag.SkewKurt == "OUT") %>%
  # Display in reactable table
  reactable()

We can see again that nsa_ta02, fr_ta04, fr_ta10, nsa_ta10, ga_ta13, nsa_ta13, fr_ta16 and nsa_ta16 have skewness and/or kurtosis outside appropriate thresholds. We can employ COINr framework to perform the task. For each indicator, the Treat() function:

  • Checks skew and kurtosis using the check_SkewKurt() function
  • If the indicator fails the test (returns FALSE), applies Winsorisation (remove extreme points)
  • Checks again skew and kurtosis
  • If the indicator still fails, applies a log transformation

We will perform such treatment and provide a summary of it:

# Treat at defaults (winsorize up to five times and -if needed- transform, to get skewness lower than 2, kurtosis lower than 3.5)
GIRAI <- Treat(GIRAI, dset = "Raw")

Data normalisation

All the indicators in Raw dataset are already normalised (and adjusted for effectiveness), since we extracted the already normalised and adjusted scores (XX_adjust_score) from the database. Again, for completeness, this is the step to follow for normalisation if it were necessary, which will need adapting for considering the different ways to normalise the different indicators (that have different theoretical ranges). The adjustment for effectiveness would have to be performed after the normalisation in that case.

# Normalise the raw data set
GIRAI <- Normalise(GIRAI, dset = "Raw")
